    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-14T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-14T20:00:00-05:00" n="406"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d406">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">340.1115A/2033a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-14T21:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 14, 1941—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1695. Your 2264, June 9.<note n="9" xml:id="d406fn9">Not printed.</note>
                        MacVeagh<note n="10" xml:id="d406fn10">Lincoln MacVeagh, Minister in
                        Greece.</note> has informed Department that he has advised you of situation
                    prevailing in Greece with regard to the delay in the issuance by the German
                    authorities of exit permits for American citizens who are desirous of returning
                    to the United States, and other offices report refusal of German authorities to
                    grant transit visas to American citizens.</p>
                <p>The Department is fully appreciative of your efforts to reach with the German
                    authorities a satisfactory solution of the whole question of the issuance of
                    exit and transit visas to Americans. Department wishes you to consider this
                    telegram as evidence of its desire now to obtain from the German authorities
                    assurance that prompt action will henceforth be taken on the applications for
                    exit permits and transit visas made by Americans in Greece and elsewhere
                    desiring to return to the United States, arrangements for which, owing to
                    disruption in means of communication and transportation, are sufficiently
                    difficult even if not complicated by the delay now being experienced in
                    obtaining exit and transit visas.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
